{{Infobox glacier | child = | name = Baker Glacier | other_name = | photo = | photo_width = | photo_alt = | photo_caption = | map = Antarctica | map_width = | map_alt = | map_caption = Location of Baker Glacier in [[Antarctica]] | mark = Blue_pog.svg | type = tributary | location = [[Victoria land]] | coordinates = {{coord|77|46|S|169|15|E|region:AQ|format=dms|display=inline}} | coords_ref = | area = | length = | width = | thickness = unknown | elevation_max = | elevation_min = | terminus = [[Whitehall Glacier]] | status = unknown | embedded = }}
'''Baker Glacier''' ({{Coord|72|46|S|169|15|E|source:GNIS|display=inline,title}}) is a small tributary [[glacier]] that enters [[Whitehall Glacier]] just north of [[Martin Hill (Antarctica)|Martin Hill]], in the [[Victory Mountains]] of [[Victoria Land]], [[Antarctica]]. It was mapped by the [[United States Geological Survey]] from surveys and from [[U.S. Navy]] air photos, 1960–62, and named by the [[Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names]] for [[John R. Baker (biologist with BAS)|John R. Baker]], biologist at [[Hallett Station]] in 1967–68 and 1968–69.
