'''Edison''' is an epic poem by Czech poet [[Vítězslav Nezval]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slovnikceskeliteratury.cz/showContent.jsp?docId=1085|title=Slovník české literatury|publisher=}}</ref> It was written in 1927.<ref>Milan Blahynka, Ediční poznámka, [in:] Vítězslav Nezval, Básně noci, Odeon, Praha 1966, p. 160. (in Czech)</ref> Later it was included in the poetic book ''Básně noci'' (''Poems of the Night'') which was published in 1930.<ref>Alfred Thomas, ''The Bohemian Body: Gender and Sexuality in Modern Czech Culture'', The University of Wisconsin Press, Madison 2007, p. 126.</ref> The main hero of the poem is American inventor [[Thomas Alva Edison]], considered by the author to be a modern genius. Nezval's work is a praise of human activity, technology, and science, but also an expression of anxiety about civilisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biskoupky.cz/index.php?action=clanek&blind=1&type=|title=Biskoupky.cz: oficiální informační portál obce Biskoupky|first=Miroslav|last=Patočka|publisher=}}</ref> Nezval compares the inventor's work to writing poetry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/V%C3%ADt%C3%A9zslav%20Nezval|title=Vítézslav Nezval|publisher=}}</ref> He points out that every creative work demands much toil and courage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edisonmuckers.org/thomas-edison-pop-culture/|title=Thomas Edison and Pop Culture|date=21 February 2012|publisher=}}</ref> After Edison's death in 1931 Nezval wrote ''Signál času'' (''Signal of time'') which is an elegy. Both poems are written in the same measure, [[Trochee|trochaic hexameter]]. Nezval uses long enumerations,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grammar.about.com/od/e/g/Enumeratio.htm|title=Enumeratio(n) in Rhetoric: Point by Point by Point|publisher=}}</ref> building sophisticated poetical imagery.<ref>Barbara Mytko, Apollinaire i czeska awangarda poetycka, Studia Rossica Posnaniensia 17, 1982/1983, pp. 67-75 (in Polish).</ref> Nezval's ''Edison'' was probably influenced by [[Guillaume Apollinaire]]'s work, especially the poem ''Zone'', which was translated into Czech by [[Karel Čapek]].<ref>[http://complit.utoronto.ca/wp-content/uploads/COL1000H_Deborah_Garfinkle.pdf Deborah Garfinkle, Karel Čapek's Pásmo and the construction of literary modernity through the art of translation, The Slavic and east European Journal, Vol. 47, No. 3 (Autumn 2003), pp. 345-366.]</ref>
== Translations == The poem was translated into English by [[Ewald Osers]]. François Kérel, helped by Nezval himself, translated the poem into French.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tnit.fr/book/edison.htm|title=V. Nezval: Edison|publisher=}}</ref> It was also twice translated into Polish, by [[Kazimierz Andrzej Jaworski]] and [[Józef Waczków]].
==Notes== {{reflist}}
